==French==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|fr|frm}}, from {{m|frm|aborder}}, from {{der|fr|fro|aborder|t=to hit a ship in order to board it}}, from {{m|fro|bord|t=side of a ship, edge}}, from {{der|fr|frk|*bord|t=side of a ship or vessel}}, from {{der|fr|gem-pro|*burdą|t=edge, border, side}}, from {{der|fr|ine-pro|*bheredh-|t=to cut}}. Cognate with {{cog|goh|bort|t=edge, rim, rand}}, {{cog|ang|bord|t=ship, side of a ship}}, {{cog|non|borð|t=edge, side of a vessel}}. More at {{l|en|board}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{fr-IPA}}
* {{audio|fr|Fr-abord.ogg|Audio}}

===Noun===
{{fr-noun|m}}

# {{lb|fr|literary}} the [[manner]] with which one acts in the [[presence]] of another person or persons, especially in a first [[encounter]]
#* {{quote-book|fr|year=2008|title=Amphibiens et reptiles|isbn=978-2-84416-650-0|page=80|passage=''Au premier '''abord''', la caouanne est une tortue à très grosse tête.''|translation=At first '''glance''', the loggerhead is a turtle with a very large head.}}
# {{lb|fr|rare}} the [[surrounding]]s of a place
# {{lb|fr|archaic}} [[arrival]] or [[accessibility]] by water

====Usage notes====
* In the sense "surroundings", the word is almost always a [[pluralia tantum]].
* The sense "manner of acting" is usually now perceived as a backformation from {{m|fr|aborder||to approach}}, and is most common in the expression {{m|fr||être [[d'un abord]]}} and variations of it.

